[start section id="20112"]

Basic cancer education has been provided to the patient at the request of Dr. Jackson Service.  I have had the opportunity to review the operative report, surgical pathology, laboratory values, and notes in Documents Browser.  I have reviewed these findings with the patient and answered questions.  I have discussed this case in detail with Dr. Lindsey Armstrong, my collaborating physician, who has guided my plan.
We have discussed the characteristics of the cancer, including the type of malignancy, size, grade, lymph node status, and stage of the cancer.
Prior to meeting with Mr. Johnson I have reviewed his case in its entirety with Dr. Lindsey Armstrong who again reiterates the recommendations that were outlined in his and Dr. Timmer note dated May 25, 2010.  Understandably Mr. Johnson had a complicated radiation chemotherapy course and needs to take that into consideration when making further recommendations.  Generally would recommend four additional months of systemic chemotherapy (FOLFOX-6), however, given the fact that Mr. Johnson has had such complications regarding the past therapy it certainly is viable to consider observation only.  I informed Mr. Johnson that this is a discussion he should have with his local oncologist who will be treating him.  This person has better knowledge of his tolerance of therapies.  I did state that one consideration could be to start the chemotherapy with a significant dose modification of the infusional 5-FU and see how things are tolerated.  Obviously the infusional 5-FU is administered over a shorter period of time and often times is better tolerated.  Also confounding his past symptoms is the fact that he was also receiving radiation therapy concurrently.  Again, this is a discussion he should have with his primary oncologist.  He understands that if he chooses observation only and if the cancer were to reoccur that then he could be treated with chemotherapy.  He had several questions that I answered to his satisfaction.  He denies any further questions or concerns.  He has our telephone number to contact us should he have any further questions or concerns.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.
The patient has agreed to return to be formally evaluated in the Decatur Valley Hospital in the postoperative setting.  Please note that this note should not be included in the dismissal summary.

